In reference to style sucus is used to denote a tawdry ornament. See Cic. de Orat. II. 45, III. 523 Quintil. VIII. 3, § 6; cf. II. 15, § 25. In this last passage Quint. alludes to a practice prevalent among mangones of painting the slaves they had for sale, which may be regarded as an illustration of the passage before us, and the object was, evidently, ut vitia corporis occulerent, &c.
